When a small group of living beings (a small population) departs from the main one they come from (for example, if they travel to a mountain chain or a river, or if they move to a new island so that they cannot easily go back down) they will often find themselves in a different environment than they used to be.
The new environment has different resources and competitors and, therefore, a new population will need different characteristics or adaptations than it had before to be a strong competitor.
There have been no changes in the original population, which still require the same adaptations as in the past.
As time passes, as the incipient population adapts to the new environment, it begins to resemble the other population less and less.
Finally, after thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will look so different that it will not be possible to catalog them as of the same species.
This process receives the name speciation, which simply means the development of new species, and is an inescapable consequence and a fundamental part of evolution.
