Technological determinism is a concept that comprises, pragmatically, a wide range of ideas, from technological impulse or imperative to a strict sense that there is an underlying logic that drives the destiny of humanity and relates to the laws of science and how they are reflected in technology.
Almost all interpretations of technological determinism have two general two ideas: that technological development itself unfolds on an independent path of any cultural or political influence and that, at the same time, technology has "effects" on societies that are inherent and not socially conditioned.
To give an example, one could hold that the existence of automobiles necessarily derives from the development of roads.
However, a national road network is not economically viable for a small volume of cars, and new manufacturing techniques are being designed to reduce the costs of owning a vehicle.
Mass use of automobiles also generates a greater incidence of traffic accidents, leading to the development of new techniques in the field of health to repair damaged bodies.
